Here's the registration setup:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Data service — one HttpClient/instance for the whole app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — new instance per request so pages get fresh state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient so each navigation creates a clean page
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why each lifetime:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient` / shared state (auth tokens, cache). One instance avoids socket exhaustion and keeps config consistent. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each navigation should start with clean state—no stale data from a previous visit. |
| Pages | **Transient** | Pairs 1-to-1 with their ViewModel. A fresh page avoids leftover UI state (scroll position, selections). |

**Key rules of thumb:**

- **Singleton** — stateless or intentionally shared (HTTP clients, caches, logging).
- **Transient** — lightweight, stateful-per-use (ViewModels, pages).
- **Scoped** — rarely used in MAUI (no per-request scope like ASP.NET), but useful if you create manual scopes for a workflow.

> ⚠️ Never inject a **transient** or **scoped** service into a **singleton** — the shorter-lived service gets captured and effectively becomes a singleton too (captive dependency problem).
